Author: Raghu Rao <raghu.v.rao@gmail.com>
=============================================================================

_____________________________________________________________________________
xterm
xterm-like terminual emulators (gnome-terminal, konsole, iTerm2 etc.)
=============================================================================

Operating System Command (OSC) sequences can be used to set the title strings.

OSC is the following sequence:

    ESC ]

OSC can be used to set xterm titles using either sequence below:

    OSC n ; TXT BEL
    OSC n ; TXT ST

BEL is the bell character (Control-G or octal 007).  ST is String Terminator
(the sequence ESC \).

I will use the first form (the one with BEL).

Title strings are modified when n is 0, 1 or 2.  3 is also a valid value for
n, but that value is not relevant to title-setting, so we will not discuss
n = 3.

_______________
OSC 0 ; TXT BEL
---------------

Set terminal emulator window title and icon name to TXT.  In some terminal
emulators that support tabs, the icon name is used for setting the tab title.
E.g. iTerm2.

_______________
OSC 1 ; TXT BEL
---------------

Set only icon name (tab title in some terminal emulators) to TXT.

_______________
OSC 2 ; TXT BEL
---------------

Set only terminal emulator window title to TXT.

When n = 0 (that is, the first of the three sequences above), it seems to do
The Right/Expected Thing on all terminal emulators I use frequently
(gnome-terminal, Konsole, iTerm2, xterm).  The second sequence above (n = 1)
does nothing on gnome-terminal, at least on some versions of it.  When n = 2,
only the tab title is set in iTerm2; the window title is not altered.  Using
the first sequence (n = 0) lets me not worry about these differences.

Let us say I want to set the title to:

    hostname(shell PID)

Example:

    inspiron1545.example.com(12345)

If I am using bash, I can use the environment variables $HOSTNAME and $$ to
get me the information I need.  The control sequence would look like:

    OSC   0 ; ${HOSTNAME}(${$}) BEL
  = ESC ] 0 ; ${HOSTNAME}(${$}) BEL
  = \e  ] 0 ; ${HOSTNAME}(${$}) \a

I could then use the bash builtin 'printf' to send this sequence just before
my prompt is printed.  The PROMPT_COMMAND variable can be used for this
purpose.  If I set the value of PROMPT_COMMAND to the following, I will have
bash set the terminal emulator window title / icon name text for me right
before each time the prompt is ready to be displayed.

    $ echo "${PROMPT_COMMAND}"
    printf '\e]0;%s(%s)\a' "${HOSTNAME}" "${$}"

To be safe, I will set PROMPT_COMMAND to the above only when TERM=xterm* (e.g.
xterm, xterm-color, xterm-256color, etc.).

_____________________________________________________________________________
GNU screen and tmux
=============================================================================

When in GNU screen and tmux, we do not set the terminal emulator window title
or icon name directly.  Instead, we set one or more variables internal to
screen or tmux, and instruct screen or tmux to use those variables to set the
window title.  How these programs set the title, I will not discuss here
(frankly, because I do not know how they do it - I have not studied their
sources).

In addition to the OSC titles above, both screen and tmux support the
following sequence:

    ESC k TXT ESC \
  = \e  k TXT \e  \\  (in bash)

Let me call this sequence KSEQ so I can refer to it easily in the rest of this
document.

KSEQ sets the tmux-/screen-window name (not the terminal emulator window title
text).  I will discuss this sequence a little more in the sections below.

__________
GNU screen
----------

In GNU screen, the relevant variable is the hardstatus of the window (yielded
by %h).  It so happens that the first of the OSC titles described above (i.e.
when n = 0) sets the hardstatus of the window in GNU screen:

    OSC 0 ; TXT BEL

You may have to define hs, ts, fs and ds in the screen configuration file
(e.g. ~/.screenrc) to get the OSC window-title/icon-name sequence to work
correctly.  For example:

    termcapinfo <term-type-glob> "hs:ts=\E]0;:fs=\007:ds=\E]0;\007"

where <term-type-glob> matches the value of the TERM environment variable
BEFORE starting screen.  For example, if you are running xterm, TERM typically
matches 'xterm*' (e.g. xterm, xterm-color, xterm-256color etc.).  So, if you
start screen in xterm, you want to put something like the following in your
screenrc.

    termcapinfo xterm* hs:ts=\E]0;:fs=\007:ds=\E]0;\007

____
tmux
----

In tmux, the relevant variables are pane_title and window_name.

The first and third OSC title sequences (n = 0 and n = 2) described above will
set variable 'pane_title'.

KSEQ described above sets the variable 'window_name'.

I have configured tmux to use both pane_title and window_name to set the
terminal emulator window title bar text.  I have done so by including the
following in my ~/.tmux.conf:

    set -g set-titles-string "#{session_alerts} #{pane_title} | #{window_name}"

In GNU screen and tmux, TERM is 'screen*'.  E.g. screen, screen-256color,
screen.linux etc.  When TERM=screen*, I use both the OSC title sequence (n
= 0) and KSEQ in PROMPT_COMMAND.  I have set the value of PROMPT_COMMAND to:

    $ echo "${PROMPT_COMMAND}"
    printf '\e]0;%s(%s)\a\ek%s(%s)\e\\' "${HOSTNAME}" "${$}" "${HOSTNAME}" "${$}"
